\subsection{Hydrology module}

The irrigation module is designed to be sufficiently flexible to be coupled with existing hydrological models, including conceptual water balance models and more complex process-based models. A default hydrology module based on the recent Spatial Processes in HYdrology model \citep{terink_sphy_2015} is included with the module.

\subsection{Model coupling}

\noindent Variables from hydrology module (i.e. VIC) $\rightarrow$ irrigation model:

\begin{itemize}
\item Water content of each soil layer in the root zone ($Z_{r}$) - irrigation module will use this to calculate $TAW$, $RAW$
\item Depth of soil layers
\item Soil properties (field capacity, water content)
\item Depth to groundwater
\item Well yield (?)
\item Canal water availability
\end{itemize}

Parameters from VIC:

veg_class
overstory
rarc (architectural resistance of vegetation type)
rmin (minimum stomatal resistance of vegetation type)
LAI (leaf area index)
albedo (shortwave albedo)
rough (vegetation roughness length - 0.123 * vegetation height)
displacement (vegegation displacement height - 0.67 vegetation height)
wind_h (height at which wind speed is measured)
RGL (minimum incoming shortwave radiation at which there will be transpiration)
rad_atten (radiation attenuation factor)
wind_atten (wind speed attenuation through the overstory)
trunk_ratio (ratio of total tree height that is trunk)

\noindent Variables from irrigation module $\rightarrow$ hydrology module:

\begin{itemize}
\item Rooting depth (VIC should 
\item Irrigation demand (surface water, groundwater)
\item Crop evapotranspiration
\end{itemize}

